
- *Corticosteroid mechanisms in post-viral fatigue integration* ([Chapter 7, 1 new hypothesis environment; Chapter 14a, new section with 2 environments; hypothesis-registry.typ, 3 new entries; hypotheses-trees/subtrees/corticosteroid-mechanisms-postviral.md, new subtree with 36 nodes]): Deeper immune/inflammatory dive into corticosteroid biology in post-viral fatigue contexts. Added T cell exhaustion hypothesis (GR-mediated transcriptional reprogramming, PD-1 upregulation, metabolic suppression) to Chapter 7. Added GR signaling section to Chapter 14a with 2 environments: GR signaling bifurcation speculation (post-viral immune states exhibit different GR signaling than acute inflammation, explaining steroid failure in Long COVID/ME/CFS) and corticosteroid timing paradox hypothesis (early administration impairs viral clearance, late administration may provide anti-inflammatory benefits). Created hypothesis subtree with 36 nodes from Phase 3 brainstorm. Integrated 3 of 36 high-utility ideas. Fixed 3 syntax errors (replaced < > with "less than"/"greater than") and 1 citation error (mandarano2020tcell_metabolism → Mandarano2020). Build verified successful. _Motivated by:_ Auto-escalation rule for immune/inflammatory topics; @Adam2024PoCoVIT trial failure prompting deeper mechanistic inquiry; existing corticosteroid literature integration gaps.

- *Methylprednisolone failure in Long COVID integration* ([Chapter 19, 8 new environments (1 warning, 4 hypotheses, 3 speculations); references.bib, 1 new entry; hypothesis-registry.typ, new section with 8 entries; Phase 3 brainstorm: 30 ideas generated across 9 categories]): Integration of negative PoCoVIT trial results demonstrating methylprednisolone ineffectiveness in Long COVID with high adverse event rate. Trial terminated early (96/418 enrolled, 5 serious AEs) with no efficacy vs placebo on any outcome. Phase 3 brainstorm generated 30 creative hypotheses across novel mechanisms, research directions, drug ideas, supplements, non-pharmacological interventions, combinations, math model extensions, cross-disease bridges, and diagnostics. Integrated 8 high-priority ideas: warning environment documenting trial failure; 4 hypotheses (corticosteroid-induced HPA "trust-breaking", viral reactivation via NK suppression, transcriptional reprogramming trap, GR isoform imbalance); 3 speculations (corticosteroids may worsen outcomes, steroid-sparing anti-inflammatory protocol, post-steroid recovery protocol, VNS as steroid alternative). Updated hypothesis registry with 8 entries. Created hypothesis subtree file with 30 nodes. _Motivated by:_ @Adam2024PoCoVIT — PoCoVIT trial terminated early due to adverse events, showing no methylprednisolone benefit in Long COVID; negative result provides cautionary evidence against corticosteroid trials in ME/CFS and spawned extensive hypothesis generation about alternative mechanisms and steroid-avoidant strategies.

- *Exercise recovery and PEM duration integration* ([Chapter 2, PEM measurement section updated; Chapter 5, severity levels section updated; Chapter 14a, core mechanisms section updated with epigenetic/EV hypotheses; Chapter 14d, cross-disease section updated with Long COVID comparison; Chapter 14f, CPET-derived section updated; Chapter 25b, proposed studies section updated; Appendix H, 11 new annotated entries; references.bib, 19 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 6 new entries]): Comprehensive integration of 20-paper literature review on 2-day CPET, PEM recovery duration, and exercise testing in ME/CFS. Updated PEM measurement section with largest 2-day CPET study (Keller2024CPET), ICF discrimination evidence, and 24h interval limitation. Added severity vs PEM recovery patterns analysis with severity-independent PEM mechanism speculation. Added CPET-2 deterioration as ME/CFS-specific signature hypothesis. Added Long COVID vs ME/CFS PEM divergence hypothesis (null result from Gattoni2025LongCOVIDCPET). Added novel mechanistic insights: prolonged epigenetic recovery hypothesis (Sharma2025EpigeneticPEM) and EV-mediated intercellular signaling speculation (Giloteaux2024EVExercise). Added comprehensive multi-timepoint PEM recovery duration study proposal to Ch25b. Updated hypothesis registry with 6 new entries (3 hypotheses, 2 speculations, 1 study). _Motivated by:_  — largest 2-day CPET study confirming Day 2 deterioration; @vanCampen2020SeverityCPET — severity patterns in 2-day CPET;  — 48h epigenetic changes post-exercise;  — EV proteome changes with exercise;  — Long COVID null result showing no CPET-2 impairment.

	- *Vascular inflammation in neuropsychiatric Long COVID integration* ([Chapter 14k, 3 new hypothesis environments, 2 new speculation environments, 4 new open-question environments; mathematical model with limitation environment; Appendix H, 1 new annotated entry; references.bib, 1 new entry; hypothesis-registry.typ, 4 new entries]): Integration of McAlpine et al. 2026 vascular biomarker study demonstrating endothelial dysfunction WITHOUT overt coagulopathy in Long COVID, with cognitive and psychiatric symptom correlations. Added novel hypotheses extending Long COVID findings to ME/CFS: endothelial adhesion-cognition correlation (0.40), AGP neuroprotective biomarker speculation (0.25), vascular biomarker temporal evolution model (0.35). Added treatment proposals: anti-adhesion therapy for cognitive symptoms, biomarker-guided ME/CFS subtype stratification. Added formal limitation environment to speculative mathematical model. Fixed citation keys to use correct bib entries. Corrected ADAMTS13 classification error (VWF-cleaving protease, not endothelial adhesion molecule). Updated hypothesis registry with 4 new entries. _Motivated by:_ @McAlpine2026 — vascular inflammation correlates with cognitive/psychiatric symptoms in Long COVID; endothelial dysfunction distinction from coagulopathy; cross-disease mechanistic parallels with ME/CFS.

- *TSPO PET imaging integration* ([Chapter 6, 1 new speculation environment; Chapter 7, 1 new limitation environment; Chapter 14k, 2 new hypothesis environments; Appendix H, 2 new annotated entries; references.bib, 8 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 2 new entries]): Integration of 8-paper literature review on TSPO PET imaging in ME/CFS, highlighting critical methodological gaps and mechanistic insights. Single published ME/CFS TSPO PET study (Raijmakers 2021, n=9) found NO neuroinflammation using first-generation tracer; no whole-body TSPO PET studies exist in PubMed. Key finding: Barzon 2026 demonstrated peripheral inflammation reduces TSPO tracer brain influx (BBB transport confounding), potentially masking neuroinflammation. Added neuroinflammation measurement limitation environment to Chapter 7. Added TSPO dual-role speculation environment to Chapter 6 (mitochondrial dysfunction vs inflammation marker). Added two hypotheses to Chapter 14k: BBB transport confounding hypothesis (explains negative TSPO PET findings) and peripheral-inflation central-starvation hypothesis (resolves paradox of elevated peripheral TSPO with decreased brain signal). Updated hypothesis registry with 2 new entries. _Motivated by:_ @Raijmakers2021TSPOCFS — single ME/CFS TSPO PET study showing null neuroinflammation finding; @Barzon2026TSPOBBB — BB B transport confounding mechanism; @VanElzakker2019TSPOReview — comprehensive TSPO biology review. Michelle James Stanford conference data (unpublished) suggests whole-body TSPO imaging would reveal "peripheral-up, central-down" pattern, but study not yet in PubMed.
	- *Shared mechanisms (fibromyalgia, ME/CFS, Long COVID) integration partial* ([Chapter 3, fibromyalgia section expanded with 2 hypothesis environments; Chapter 3, dizziness section expanded with dysautonomia subsection and achievement environment; Chapter 5, subgroups section expanded with overlap-based subgroups; Chapter 5, trigger mechanisms section expanded with biological convergence and terrain+trigger hypothesis; Appendix H, 10 new annotated entries; references.bib, 10 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 3 new entries]): Partial integration of Dr. Rémy Honoré's clinical review (May 2026) synthesizing evidence that fibromyalgia, ME/CFS, and Long COVID share core biological mechanisms. Added neuroinflammation hypothesis (certainty 0.55, reduced from 0.70 after adversarial review) with microglial activation via TSPO PET evidence; central sensitization hypothesis (certainty 0.70) demonstrating shared pain amplification across conditions; terrain+trigger model (certainty 0.60) for post-infectious ME/CFS with pre-existing vulnerability factors. Added overlap statistics (30-50% Long COVID meets ME/CFS criteria, 20-70% fibromyalgia presents ME/CFS-compatible picture) with explicit limitation noting wide range reflects heterogeneity. Created dysautonomia subsection with POTS prevalence data (20-40% Long COVID, 25-50% ME/CFS, >30% fibromyalgia) and objective autonomic testing achievement environment. Fixed critical compilation issues (duplicate section, missing bibliography entry, broken cross-references) and 3 adversarial review findings (safety warnings for speculative permanent function loss, certainty calibration for neuroinflammation, overlap range clarification). Phase 4 integration partial (44 brainstorming ideas remain); Phase 6 adversarial review partial (18 findings remain for follow-up session). Created hypothesis subtree with 4 nodes; brainstorm file with 50 ideas across 9 categories. _Motivated by:_ @Honore2026sharedMechanisms — clinical review establishing shared mechanisms across fibromyalgia, ME/CFS, and Long COVID; @Albrecht2019neuroinflammationFM — PET imaging showing activated microglia in fibromyalgia; @Meeus2007centralSensitizationCFS — QST demonstrating central sensitization in ME/CFS; @Eldokla2022autonomicLongCOVID — POTS prevalence and autonomic testing in Long COVID; @Wong2021LongCOVIDMECFS — systematic review of Long COVID ME/CFS overlap.

	- *Connective tissue disorders integration* ([Chapter 13, new section with 1 hypothesis environment; Chapter 14a, new section with 1 hypothesis environment; Chapter 14k, new subsection with dysautonomia prevalence data; Appendix H, 10 new annotated entries; references.bib, 10 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 2 new entries]): Integration of connective tissue disorders (CTDs) in ME/CFS, focusing on bidirectional relationship with ME/CFS pathophysiology. Added bidirectional CTD-ME/CFS relationship hypothesis to Chapter 13 (certainty 0.45) with evidence for: (1) CTD predisposition via hypermobility (30-57% in ME/CFS vs 10-15% general population), craniocervical instability, autonomic dysfunction, and mast cell hyperactivity; (2) ME/CFS exacerbation of CTD via ROS-mediated inhibition of prolyl hydroxylases (impairing collagen crosslinking), chronic HIF-1$alpha$ elevation (altering extracellular matrix composition), mast cell activation (MMP-mediated collagen degradation), and basement membrane thickening in capillaries (impairing perfusion). Added HIF-1$alpha$-mediated connective tissue remodeling hypothesis to Chapter 14a (certainty 0.55) linking tendinopathy mechanisms (direct ECM alteration, VEGF-independent pathology, MMP-3-mediated degradation) to ME/CFS connective tissue pathology. Added dysautonomia prevalence data to Chapter 14k: 64% dysautonomia prevalence in chronic musculoskeletal pain (meta-analysis N=1420, RR=2.28 vs controls), POTS comorbidities (31% hypermobility, 36.3% MCAS, 40.9% chronic fatigue), and hEDS/HSD patient experience data (diagnostic delay 19-21 years, 45.6% unemployment). Updated hypothesis registry with 2 new entries. _Motivated by:_ @Wirth2026CTDMECFS — preprint proposing bidirectional CTD-ME/CFS relationship and linking ROS, HIF-1$alpha$, mast cell pathways to connective tissue pathology; @Ganesh2024LongCOVIDHSD — hypermobility prevalence data and Long COVID-HSD shared pathophysiology; @Ramirez-Paesano2023CCI — craniocervical instability producing ME/CFS-like symptoms in EDS; @Moschini2026HIFTendinopathy — HIF-1$alpha$ as driver (not marker) of tendinopathy with direct ECM alteration; @Sahin2012HIFTendon — HIF-1$alpha$/VEGF/MMP-3 cascade reducing biomechanical stability; @Almutairi2026DysautonomiaMSD — dysautonomia meta-analysis in chronic musculoskeletal pain; @Kulin2026POTSGI — POTS GI symptoms and comorbidities meta-analysis; @Berg2026HSDSurvey — hEDS/HSD lived experience survey; @Wilson2026hEDSWearable — hEDS wearable monitoring of autonomic dysfunction; @Eccles2021hypermobility — hypermobility prevalence in ME/CFS/FM clinic population.


	- *Cryotherapy and cold exposure for sleep quality* ([Chapter 17, new Section `sec:cold-sleep-warning`; Appendix H, new Section `sec:cold-alternatives`; references.bib, 12 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 2 new entries]): Integration of cryotherapy and cold exposure evidence for sleep quality, pain reduction, and autonomic regulation, with explicit 14 contraindications for ME/CFS patients due to thermoregulatory dysfunction and autonomic instability. Key findings: WBC improves sleep and autonomic function in healthy populations (parasympathetic activation, increased slow-wave sleep, pain reduction) @Douzi2018SleepCryotherapy; ME/CFS patients have documented thermoregulatory dysfunction impairing adaptive responses to cold stress @Li2021ThermoregulationCFS @Cambras2018CircadianCFS; only direct CFS WBC study (Kujawski 2023) showed mixed results with high attrition (45%) @Kujawski2023CBSCFS; cold exposure contraindications for dysautonomia/POTS explicitly listed in safety guidelines @Tipton2017ColdWaterSafety. Home-based alternatives discussed: cold water immersion (10–15°C, 2–5 min, contraindicated for dysautonomia), cold showers (3–5 min, minimal sleep evidence), cold face immersion (safest vagal stimulation option) @Zaproudil2020ColdVagal. _Motivated by:_ User question about ME/CFS hypersensitivity and thermoregulation issues — comprehensive literature review found thermoregulatory dysfunction contraindicates cold exposure without clinical supervision.


- *Kynurenine-Sleep-Mitochondria-Excitotoxicity Feedback Loop Integration* ([Chapter 14c, new hypothesis environment; Appendix H, new annotated entries; references.bib, 9 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 1 new entry]): Integrated multi-system feedback loop hypothesis connecting kynurenine pathway activation, sleep architecture disruption, mitochondrial dysfunction, and glutamate excitotoxicity in ME/CFS. [Mechanistic loop: immune activation → IDO → tryptophan shunt → elevated QA:KYNA ratio and NAD+ depletion → mitochondrial dysfunction → ATP depletion → Na+/K+ pump collapse → EAAT2 impairment → glutamate accumulation → excitotoxicity → neuroinflammation → IDO activation. Parallel: sleep disruption → glymphatic impairment → metabolite accumulation. Evidence from 12 papers (kynurenine, sleep, mitochondrial, EAAT2) with clinical ME/CFS data (Che2025, Chojnacki2026) and mechanistic extrapolation from related conditions (Cervenka2017, Xie2013, Rothstein1996). Added 8 Tier 1 research directions (glymphatic clearance rate, mitochondrial-EAAT2 coupling, probiotic stratification, longitudinal kynurenine profiling, muscle clearance capacity, sirtuin threshold, brainstem glutamate, KMO redox sensitivity) and 10 Tier 1–2 treatment approaches to therapeutic implications. Created hypothesis subtree with 70 nodes and updated root index. _Motivated by:_ @Cervenka2017, @Schwarcz2012 — foundational kynurenine pathway reviews establishing IDO activation, NAD+ depletion, and dual QA/KYNA effects; @Che2025, @Chojnacki2026 — ME/CFS multi-omics and clinical trial showing kynurenine pathway dysregulation and probiotic-mediated improvement; @Xie2013glymphatic — sleep-driven glymphatic clearance mechanism linking SWS to metabolite removal; @Rothstein1996 — EAAT2 knockout demonstrating Na+/K+ pump dependence for glutamate clearance; @Elbaga2026, @Manisha2026, @Zhang2026PirBEAAT2 — EAAT2 impairment in neurodegenerative disease models providing mechanistic basis for extrapolation to ME/CFS; @FanoIllic2026SkeletalMuscle, @Jin2026PEMMechanism, @Zhang2026MitochondriaFatigue — ME/CFS mitochondrial dysfunction and genetic evidence supporting energy metabolism impairment.


	- *Wirth-Scheibenbogen 2026 Update Integration* ([Chapter 6, calcium toxicity hypothesis updated with mechanistic scope limitation; Chapter 14b, immunoadsorption trial results updated with Berlin 2026 conference findings; Chapter 14, treatment map updated with AIMM subtype analysis; Chapter 21, clinical trials registry updated; Appendix H, new annotated entry; references.bib, 1 new entry]): Updated existing Wirth-Scheibenbogen calcium overload hypothesis coverage with new 2026 clinical trial results and mechanistic scope analysis. Key findings: IA-PACS-CFS sham-controlled RCT (n=65) showed no statistically significant difference between immunoadsorption and sham groups on Chalder Fatigue Scale, but criticism emerged that trial did not preselect antibody-positive patients—subgroup analysis pending. Charité case series (n=15 antibody-positive patients) showed 7 responders, suggesting subtype-specific effect. EXTINCT, Mainz, and Hannover trials completed but results not yet released. Added mechanistic scope limitation to AIMM hypothesis: calcium toxicity cascade is DOWNSTREAM of four Tier 1 trigger-capable mechanisms (CNS energy crisis, metabolic safe mode lock, GPCR autoantibody cascade, TRPM3 channelopathy). MDC002 expected to benefit only AIMM-dominant subtype (~30–40% of patients) with sodium MRI-confirmed overload, exercise-triggered PEM, and muscle-ischemic symptoms dominant over CNS symptoms. Consistent with Wirth's position that "severely ill patients will need multiple medications," best results expected from combination therapy (MDC002 + upstream mechanism-targeted interventions). Beta-cell targeting trials mentioned as next-generation approach to prevent autoantibody rebound. Build verified successful with minor formatting warnings (double asterisks). _Motivated by:_ @Rucker2026WirthScheibenbogen — The Sick Times article summarizing Wirth-Scheibenbogen hypothesis state, Berlin 2026 conference preliminary immunoadsorption RCT results, and mechanistic scope discussion; IA-PACS-CFS negative sham-controlled result challenging autoantibody hypothesis at population level but suggesting antibody-positive subgroup benefit.
